description.text:
*Edit: I redesigned the offset part so that the camera tilts over its center of mass rather than its lense. In addition, the offset part can now be printed without support. Roll axis arm is now 4mm shorter.

I'm always trying to get aerial video as smooth as possible and this gimbal is designed to do just that. It is still in development but the aim is to 3d print a light but sturdy gimbal that produces professional grade video without jello or other nasty effects.

I have designed this gimbal to work with my Tarot ZYZ22 gimbal controller and Quanum 2208 motors. The ZYZ22 controller mount is included in the thing files. The gimbal should work with other controllers as well. I haven't yet desinged any 3d printable vibration isolator as I use this one from Hobbyking.

Features:

  • Tilt motor arm is adjustable for getting good balance
  • GoPro lense is centered as close to roll axis as possible which removes annoying wobbling from video
  • Easy to print, robust shapes and no long bridges
  • Gopro can be secured with a Velcro fastener
  • GoPro filter can be attached

All holes are for M3 nuts and bolts, except two smaller M2 holes for ZYZ22 controller board. I recommend to put some thin foam under the camera to make the GoPro holder nice and tight.

Please print and test the gimbal and feel free to comment and suggest your ideas!

PID-tuning can be a pain in the ass but it is an absolute key to get perfect video quality. A good deal of the jitters and flaws derive from bad PID-tuning, not only from poor vibration isolation or unbalanced propellers.

First test (tested with poor pid tuning...) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OcXbtAqZd9U&feature=youtu.be. More videos will be coming :)

Yes,
Let me tell you my idea....
Since the part before was connected to the X axis, the oscillations of the threaded rod would affect the x position of the extruder. Now with this part you designed we still can move up/down in the Z but the oscillations of the rod are not transmitted to the X axis so the extruder will be more stable....
Now my problem is at some point the Z motors could not push up the X mechanism... after a certain Z, they would push the X mechanism without problems....
So right now I just took the rods and inverted them (the up ends of the rods are now attached to the motors)
So far I have moved it a bit and seems to work fine... lets hope it remains that way.... It seems that there is was a bit of damage in the threading...
I still see a lot of oscillation... that well it is not transmitted to the X axis mechanism... but looks strange to me...
Is there a particular way you attach the threaded rods to the motors to avoid oscillations due to a bad position? or you just tie the screws and you pay no particular attention?
comments.author: viper2097

comments.text:
Ok, fine.
I first mount the coupler to the motor, and try to tighten it as straigth as possible. Then i let the motor rotate to see if it is really straigth.
Then i put in the threaded rod until it hits the motor axis. And pull it back out ~2mm. So that the threaded rod is not hitting the motor axis inside the coupling.
Then, I'm slowly rotating the threaded rod by hand during tighten the bolts on the coupler for the threaded rod.
I get quite good results with that method.

description.text:
Greetings!,

So I loved Warhammer Realms for almost all my life. And I also happen to have a remarkable 3D printer - 3DGence ONE. Decided to mix those two and see what happens.

The Chaos Warrior has two different axes and a torn-off head hanging by the belt. Has a Khorne Logo on his helmet. The Knight has a Grail (a fake one, obviously) by his belt and Montfort insignia on shield and armour.

Those were originally designed as torture tests for supports - all kinds are required to make those print well. All kinds of angles, both ground-up and mid-print supports, bulky elements and fragile detail - it's all there. So if you want to check what your printer is made of - give these a shot!

Scaling is way off and the Chaos Warrior may have issues but none that Netfabb wouldn't sort. I will upload refined versions later. For FFF printing I'd suggest printing them as big as possible but that's up to you! They also come out perfect for SLA (Formlabs F2 users - rejoice!)

I am a SOLIDWORKS user and created it with lofts.

1) Sketch a basic curve to the part.
2) Create a loft between two points and two other profiles (I used circles with lines going horizontally through the top and bottom, then trimmed the excess). SOLIDWORKS will not let you do both points at the same time; create two separate loft features and use selection manager. You'll need to create reference planes to sketch.
3) Create extruded cylinder for handle. You'll need another plane to sketch.
4) Add a cut revolve to the handle for grip.
5) Loft between the three bodies (2 earlier lofts and the 1 extrude).
6) Add a cut down between the prongs to help grasp the weed root.
7) Add a fillet to the top of the handle.

description.text:
This is a refrigerator magnet based on the band Junip's logo. I traced both their whale and their tricky ink-splatter logo in SketchUp and made a backing piece.

There are two holes on the back which fit 1" x 3/4" rectangular magnets. You can download the SketchUp file and modify the hole sizes if you want to use other kinds of magnets.

The top part of the whale hangs over the top edge of the backing piece, so a little support is needed. I made very simple supports in SketchUp that worked reasonably well, but not perfectly. You can see the result I achieved in the pictures.

I'm providing two STLs, with and without support, as well as the SketchUp file with both versions.

I chose a grey-scale color scheme and swapped out filament at the proper heights to get a white background, black text and a grey whale.

description.text:
This is a little addition to the Filament Extruder Detector v3 by flipper:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:454584

I noticed that during "intense" printing sections (where the toolhead jitters rapidly) the sensor had difficulty making an accurate reading of the filament diameter.

I figured I could reduce the shaking by firmly attaching the sensor to the toolhead. This piece slots into the holes where the two locking bolts can be seen from the top of the Lulzbot Mini Extruder v2 toolhead (https://www.lulzbot.com/store/tool-heads/lulzbot-mini-tool-head-v2).

It certainly improved the measurements for me - I hope it helps you too!
Note that this does not add any a little under 1cm to the distance between the extruder and the sensor.

I eventually decided on a kind of 'field of shapes' thing given that the board was already punctuated by hundreds of circular holes.
It would have been much easier to engrave first, then drill but hey, sometimes things don't happen in the right order! I have put up the .svg for the layout however so that others can do it in the right order.
There is significance in the name of this cribbage board, but it might take you a while to realise..
The typeface I used is Cooper Black.

• Get a piece of wood, at least 290mm x 88mm x 20mm.
  • Engrave the attached .svg into it.
  • Drill the holes marked in red on the .svg (you could engrave these to a shallower depth to help identify them). Drill to half the depth of the material. I'm pretty sure I used a 2.5mm bit..
  • Cut the wood on a bandsaw around the outline and sand to finish.
  • Play with matches! Not in a firey sense, in a cribbage sense.

title: Concentric Apple - Math Art by Dizingof

description.text:
Concentric Apple.

2 separate designs of a concentric Apple surface equation:
x = cos(u) (4 + 3.8 cos(v))
y = sin(u) (4 + 3.8 cos(v))
z = (cos(v)+sin(v)-1) (1+sin(v)) log(1-pi v/10)+7.5 sin(v)

For 2 nozzles FDM 3D printer - use PVA filament for support structures (dissolves in water).
Else 3d print with SLS Nylon, UV resin (Formlabs Form 2) 3d printers etc..
